<doc id="173981" wikidata="Q8216221" url="?curid=173981" title="Uncorrelatedness (probability theory)">
<text>In probability theory and statistics, two real-valued random variables, formula_1, formula_2, are said to be uncorrelated if their covariance, formula_3, is zero. If two variables are uncorrelated, there is no linear relationship between them.

Uncorrelated random variables have a Pearson correlation coefficient, when it exists, of zero, except in the trivial case when either variable has zero variance (is a constant). In this case the correlation is undefined.

In general, uncorrelatedness is not the same as orthogonality, except in the special case where at least one of the two random variables has an expected value of 0. In this case, the covariance is the expectation of the product, and formula_1 and formula_2 are uncorrelated if and only if formula_6.

If formula_1 and formula_2 are independent, with finite second moments, then they are uncorrelated. However, not all uncorrelated variables are independent.

==Definition==
===Definition for two real random variables===
Two random variables formula_9 are called uncorrelated if their covariance formula_10 is zero. Formally:

===Definition for two complex random variables===
Two complex random variables formula_11 are called uncorrelated if their covariance formula_12 and their pseudo-covariance formula_13 is zero, i.e.

formula_14

===Definition for more than two random variables===
A set of two or more random variables formula_15 is called uncorrelated if each pair of them is uncorrelated. This is equivalent to the requirement that the non-diagonal elements of the autocovariance matrix formula_16 of the random vector formula_17 are all zero. The autocovariance matrix is defined as:
:formula_18

==Examples of dependence without correlation ==
===Example 1===
* Let formula_1 be a random variable that takes the value 0 with probability 1/2, and takes the value 1 with probability 1/2.
* Let formula_2 be a random variable, &quot;independent&quot; of formula_1, that takes the value −1 with probability 1/2, and takes the value 1 with probability 1/2.
* Let formula_22 be a random variable constructed as formula_23.
The claim is that formula_22 and formula_1 have zero covariance (and thus are uncorrelated), but are not independent.

