where formula_37 are formula_11 matrices. The condition for formula_2 to be symplectic is equivalent to the two following equivalent conditionsformula_40 symmetric, and formula_41formula_42 symmetric, and formula_43The second condition comes from the fact that if formula_2 is symplectic, then formula_45 is also symplectic. When formula_46 these conditions reduce to the single condition formula_32. Thus a formula_48 matrix is symplectic iff it has unit determinant.

==== Inverse matrix of block matrix ====
With formula_5 in standard form, the inverse of formula_2 is given by
formula_51
The group has dimension formula_18. This can be seen by noting that formula_53 is anti-symmetric. Since the space of anti-symmetric matrices has dimension formula_54 the identity formula_55 imposes formula_56 constraints on the formula_57 coefficients of formula_2 and leaves formula_2 with formula_18 independent coefficients.

==Symplectic transformations==

In the abstract formulation of linear algebra, matrices are replaced with linear transformations of finite-dimensional vector spaces. The abstract analog of a symplectic matrix is a symplectic transformation of a symplectic vector space. Briefly, a symplectic vector space formula_61 is a formula_62-dimensional vector space formula_63 equipped with a nondegenerate, skew-symmetric bilinear form formula_64 called the symplectic form.

A symplectic transformation is then a linear transformation formula_65 which preserves formula_64, i.e.
:formula_67
Fixing a basis for formula_63, formula_64 can be written as a matrix formula_5 and formula_71 as a matrix formula_2. The condition that formula_71 be a symplectic transformation is precisely the condition that &quot;M&quot; be a symplectic matrix:
:formula_74

Under a change of basis, represented by a matrix &quot;A&quot;, we have
:formula_75
:formula_76
One can always bring formula_5 to either the standard form given in the introduction or the block diagonal form described below by a suitable choice of &quot;A&quot;.

==The matrix Ω==
Symplectic matrices are defined relative to a fixed nonsingular, skew-symmetric matrix formula_5. As explained in the previous section, formula_5 can be thought of as the coordinate representation of a nondegenerate skew-symmetric bilinear form. It is a basic result in linear algebra that any two such matrices differ from each other by a change of basis.

The most common alternative to the standard formula_5 given above is the block diagonal form
:formula_81
This choice differs from the previous one by a permutation of basis vectors.

Sometimes the notation formula_82 is used instead of formula_5 for the skew-symmetric matrix. This is a particularly unfortunate choice as it leads to confusion with the notion of a complex structure, which often has the same coordinate expression as formula_5 but represents a very different structure. A complex structure formula_82 is the coordinate representation of a linear transformation that squares to formula_86, whereas formula_5 is the coordinate representation of a nondegenerate skew-symmetric bilinear form. One could easily choose bases in which formula_82 is not skew-symmetric or formula_5 does not square to formula_86.

Given a hermitian structure on a vector space, formula_82 and formula_5 are related via
:formula_93
where formula_94 is the metric. That formula_82 and formula_5 usually have the same coordinate expression (up to an overall sign) is simply a consequence of the fact that the metric &quot;g&quot; is usually the identity matrix.

==Diagonalization and decomposition==
*For any positive definite symmetric formula_1 real symplectic matrix formula_98, there is a symplectic unitary formula_99, formula_100such thatformula_101where the diagonal elements of formula_102 are the eigenvalues of formula_98.

*Any real symplectic matrix has a polar decomposition of the form:formula_104whereformula_105 andformula_106

*Any real symplectic matrix can be decomposed as a product of three matrices:formula_107where formula_108 and formula_109 are both symplectic and orthogonal, and formula_102 is positive-definite and diagonal. This decomposition is closely related to the singular value decomposition of a matrix and is known as an &#x27;Euler&#x27; or &#x27;Bloch-Messiah&#x27; decomposition.

* The set of orthogonal symplectic matrices forms a (maximal) compact subgroup of the symplectic group. This set is isomorphic to the set of unitary matrices of dimension formula_111, formula_112. Every symplectic orthogonal matrix can be written as
\begin{pmatrix}
I_n &amp; i I_n \\
I_n &amp; -i I_n
\end{pmatrix} \right]^\dagger \begin{pmatrix}
V &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; V^*
\end{pmatrix} \left[\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{pmatrix}
I_n &amp; i I_n \\
I_n &amp; -i I_n
\end{pmatrix} \right],
&lt;/math&gt;|}}
with formula_113.
This equation implies that every symplectic orthogonal matrix has determinant equal to +1 and thus that this is true for all symplectic matrices as its polar decomposition is itself given in terms symplectic matrices.

==Complex matrices==

If instead &quot;M&quot; is a matrix with complex entries, the definition is not standard throughout the literature. Many authors adjust the definition above to

where &quot;M*&quot; denotes the conjugate transpose of &quot;M&quot;. In this case, the determinant may not be 1, but will have absolute value 1. In the 2×2 case (&quot;n&quot;=1), &quot;M&quot; will be the product of a real symplectic matrix and a complex number of absolute value 1.

Other authors retain the definition () for complex matrices and call matrices satisfying () &quot;conjugate symplectic&quot;.

==Applications==

Transformations described by symplectic matrices play an important role in quantum optics and in continuous-variable quantum information theory. For instance, symplectic matrices can be used to describe Gaussian (Bogoliubov) transformations of a quantum state of light. In turn, the Bloch-Messiah decomposition () means that such an arbitrary Gaussian transformation can be represented as a set of two passive linear-optical interferometers (corresponding to orthogonal matrices &quot;O&quot; and &quot;O&#x27; &quot;) intermitted by a layer of active non-linear squeezing transformations (given in terms of the matrix &quot;D&quot;). In fact, one can circumvent the need for such &quot;in-line&quot; active squeezing transformations if two-mode squeezed vacuum states are available as a prior resource only.

