whence

:formula_93

A bilinear form formula_87 will be represented by a matrix formula_44 such that formula_103, once a basis of formula_88 is chosen, and conversely an formula_36 matrix formula_44 on formula_107 gives rise to a form sending formula_108 to formula_109 For each of symmetric, skew-symmetric and alternating forms, the representing matrices are symmetric, skew-symmetric and alternating respectively.

== Infinitesimal rotations ==
== Coordinate-free ==
More intrinsically (i.e., without using coordinates), skew-symmetric linear transformations on a vector space formula_88 with an inner product may be defined as the bivectors on the space, which are sums of simple bivectors (2-blades) formula_111 The correspondence is given by the map formula_112 where formula_113 is the covector dual to the vector formula_114; in orthonormal coordinates these are exactly the elementary skew-symmetric matrices. This characterization is used in interpreting the curl of a vector field (naturally a 2-vector) as an infinitesimal rotation or &quot;curl&quot;, hence the name.

== Skew-symmetrizable matrix ==
An formula_36 matrix formula_44 is said to be skew-symmetrizable if there exists an invertible diagonal matrix formula_117 such that formula_118 is skew-symmetric. For real formula_36 matrices, sometimes the condition for formula_117 to have positive entries is added.

